    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:6ed2a385-0547-44d1-bfbf-f495bb4ba46a",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 39-year-old woman who arrives to clinic looking tired but well groomed, dressed in office-casual clothes and carrying a large reusable coffee tumbler. She sits upright at first but occasionally shifts forward and presses a hand lightly over the upper abdomen when describing a burning sensation rising from her chest toward her throat. Her voice is clear, though she mentions a sour taste in her mouth on waking and intermittent hoarseness after late meals. She is not in acute distress, and her overall appearance suggests a busy professional who has been trying to manage symptoms on her own for months.\n\nShe works full time in project coordination for a marketing firm, a job that often involves irregular lunch breaks, long periods at a desk, and frequent deadline-related stress. She lives with her partner and a school-aged daughter, and most evenings are a rush of commuting, dinner preparation, and catching up on work messages after the household has settled. She enjoys cooking, weekend walks, and meeting friends for brunch, but she admits that spicy foods, tomato-based dishes, chocolate, and wine have become less enjoyable because they often trigger symptoms.\n\nOver the last year, {patientName} has developed recurrent heartburn several times per week, worse after large meals and when lying down soon after eating. She describes postprandial burning behind the sternum, regurgitation of acidic fluid, bloating, and occasional nighttime cough that disrupts sleep. To cope, she has started sleeping with extra pillows and often chews antacids from her handbag. She drinks two to three coffees daily, sometimes skips breakfast, and tends to eat her largest meal late in the evening.\n\nSocially, {patientName} is active and close with her family, though she has recently become frustrated by how symptoms affect meals out and sleep quality. She does not smoke, drinks alcohol socially on weekends, and has little time for structured exercise beyond walking. Friends describe her as dependable and energetic, but she says she feels increasingly worn down by interrupted sleep and the need to constantly think about what and when she can eat."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0a48e230-9266-4062-9cf7-442642781904",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has had intermittent reflux symptoms for roughly 10 to 12 months, becoming more frequent over the last 4 months. She reports heartburn at least four days per week and regurgitation several nights per week, especially after late dinners, coffee, wine, and spicy meals. She has self-treated with over-the-counter antacids with partial short-term relief. She denies dysphagia, haematemesis, melena, persistent vomiting, or unintentional weight loss.\n\nPast medical history is notable for overweight status and episodic stress-related insomnia, but no known peptic ulcer disease or chronic liver disease. She was hospitalized only once in early adulthood for appendicitis requiring appendectomy. She does not smoke and has no illicit drug use. Alcohol intake is light to moderate, usually one to two glasses of wine on weekends. Lifestyle contributors include sedentary desk work, frequent caffeine intake, late evening meals, and lying down within an hour of dinner when exhausted.\n\nShe has no prior upper endoscopy and no history suggesting complicated reflux. Menstrual history is unremarkable, and she is not currently pregnant. Symptom pattern and absence of alarm signs are consistent with uncomplicated GERD without oesophagitis."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}